<a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=151091">Laleini Windsong</a><br>60 Enchantress<br>Fennin Ro</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/uceriliusvz.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Cerilius VZ</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Apprentice</span><br> <font color=#ffffff>(6/18/02 6:29:17 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub23.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm27.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=81.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Confused on debuffing and nullify magic</span><hr size=1> Nullify Magic is random, to an extent. It usually takes off buffs near the top of your buff list, but if you're not lucky it can skip as many as 5 buffs in a row.<br>
<br>
The higher the level of the person who casts the effect on you, the harder it is to dispel it off. If a druid 5-8 levels above you casts WD on you, for instance, there's a good chance Nullify Magic will skip WD, maybe even several times, and take off your buffs first. The best thing to do in a circumstance like that is pray. (Crystallized pumice is also an option, as it has a 3-second casting time and no recast delay.)<br>
<br>
I haven't gotten around to testing what Nullify Magic does if you have newbie buffs (~30 levels below you) under your normal buffs (maybe it would be likely to take off those first, regardless of how deep they are).<br>
<br>
Then again, you could always wait until 53 and get Annul Magic, which is an extremely powerful upgrade -- the difference between it and Nullify is like night and day. It will almost always take off the top two buffs, and only *occasionally* will it take off the first and the third. If you get dotted by someone 5-7 levels above you, there's only a 10-20% chance it will skip the dot.<br>
